cd ~/github/sw-embed/sw-cor24-plsw && gh issue create --title "Pointer dereference (->) fails when multiple BASED records are defined across includes" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Problem

When two or more BASED records are defined (e.g., via separate %INCLUDE files), the `->` operator fails to resolve fields from records defined in earlier includes.

**Works** (one BASED record):
```bash
./scripts/build.sh include/descr.msw src/test.plsw   # OK
```

```plsw
/* descr.msw defines: DCL 1 DESCR BASED, 3 DTAG BYTE, ... */
%INCLUDE descr;
DCL D1(6) BYTE;
MAIN: PROC;
    DCL DPTR PTR;
    DPTR = ADDR(D1);
    DPTR->DTAG = 0;   /* Works fine */
END;
```

**Fails** (two BASED records):
```bash
./scripts/build.sh include/descr.msw include/heap.msw src/test.plsw
# CODEGEN ERROR: undefined field in pointer dereference
```

```plsw
/* descr.msw defines: DCL 1 DESCR BASED, 3 DTAG BYTE, ... */
/* heap.msw defines: DCL 1 OBJHDR BASED, 3 OKIND BYTE, ... */
%INCLUDE descr;
%INCLUDE heap;
DCL D1(6) BYTE;
MAIN: PROC;
    DCL DPTR PTR;
    DPTR = ADDR(D1);
    DPTR->DTAG = 0;   /* FAILS: undefined field */
END;
```

## Expected behavior

The `->` operator should resolve the field name against all known BASED records, or the pointer variable should be associated with a specific BASED type so the compiler knows which record's fields to use.

## How PL/I handles this

In PL/I, BASED variables are explicitly typed:

```pli
DCL 1 DESCR BASED(DPTR),
      3 DTAG FIXED BIN(8);
DCL DPTR POINTER;
DPTR->DTAG = 0;   /* Compiler knows DPTR uses DESCR layout */
```

The pointer is bound to its BASED declaration. Multiple BASED records coexist because each pointer knows its own record type.

## Reproduction

In sw-cor24-snobol4:
```bash
./scripts/build.sh include/descr.msw include/heap.msw src/test_minimal.plsw
```

## Impact

The SNOBOL4 project needs multiple BASED records (DESCR for descriptors, OBJHDR for heap headers, STROBJ for strings, SYMOBJ for symbol cells). Without this, each module can only use one BASED record, which defeats the purpose of the structured layout system.
